"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Ecclesiastes chapters 10–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-ecclesiastes-10-12.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ecclesiastes.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/ecclesiastes.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/ecclesiastes.json (existing: only 12:13 present)
- scripts/zc-christ-ecclesiastes-1-4.py (establishes hevel/vapor, "under the sun" framework)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 10: mostly sapiential proverbs about folly/wisdom → "theme" or "revelation of God" classification;
  connections made to NT wisdom-of-cross material (1 Cor 1:18-25) and ethical teaching
- Ch 11: generosity and divine mystery → "shadow" for sowing/dying-grain image; "revelation of God"
  for Creator's mystery; "theme" for eschatological frame
- Ch 12: the aging allegory (vv 1–7) → "shadow" for the death-and-resurrection trajectory;
  v 7 treated as thematically direct; v 11 "one Shepherd" as a type anticipating John 10;
  v 14 as the clearest eschatological verse, treated as direct in its NT fulfillment
- 12:13 already in file — skipped in this script
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ECCLESIASTES = {
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>A theme: one dead fly in the perfumer's ointment corrupts the whole. The proverbial logic applies to wisdom itself — a single folly can undo an established reputation. The NT develops this as a warning: a little leaven leavens the whole lump (1 Cor 5:6; Gal 5:9). Christ alone is the one whose wisdom is untainted; the one who knew no sin (2 Cor 5:21) is the only teacher whose instruction is not contaminated by the folly it diagnoses.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A theme: the wise heart inclines to the right, the fool's to the left. This spatial metaphor for moral orientation runs through wisdom literature. The NT locates Christ at the right hand of God (Heb 1:3; Col 3:1), the definitive orientation of all true wisdom. The cross, which appeared as folly and weakness — a thing of the left — was in fact the right hand of God's power (1 Cor 1:24-25).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A theme: the fool's folly is self-revealing even in ordinary travel — his judgment fails and he broadcasts his folly to everyone. The NT applies the same exposure to those who reject the wisdom of God: what is hidden is made manifest (Luke 8:17). The cross, conversely, exposes the folly of the wise: 'God chose the foolish things of the world to shame the wise' (1 Cor 1:27).</p>",
    "4": "<p>A revelation of God: composure can defuse even serious offenses against a ruler. The verse reveals a dimension of God's character — his patience and the possibility of de-escalation even when anger is justified. Christ embodies this composure before Pilate: 'He gave him no answer' (John 19:9), and before his accusers he was led as a sheep to slaughter, not opening his mouth (Acts 8:32, citing Isa 53:7). The composure that secures pardon is his.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A theme: there is a persistent blunder observable in human societies — those in power make disordered appointments, elevating fools and sidelining the capable. The Preacher names it as an evil 'under the sun.' The NT traces this disorder to the fall and its corrupted power structures (Rom 8:20-21; 1 Cor 2:6-8: the rulers of this age who crucified the Lord of glory). All human governance operates within this fallen disorder until Christ's kingdom comes.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A revelation of God: fools in high positions, the capable in lowly ones. This inversion of proper order is one of the book's recurring social observations. The NT's great reversal — the Magnificat's 'he has brought down the mighty from their thrones and exalted those of humble estate' (Luke 1:52) — is the eschatological answer: the order disrupted by the fall will be restored, and the capable who were assigned lowly places will be exalted in the kingdom of the one who himself took the lowest place (Phil 2:7-11).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A theme: the servant class riding and the noble class walking — social order inverted. This observation connects to the kingdom's inversion of rank: Christ came 'not to be served but to serve' (Mark 10:45), taking the servant's position himself. The one to whom all service is owed washed his disciples' feet (John 13:1-17); the social inversion the Preacher laments will be finally corrected when every knee bows (Phil 2:10-11).</p>",
    "8": "<p>A theme: whoever digs a pit may fall in it; whoever breaks through a wall may be bitten. The irony of evil returning upon its author runs through Wisdom literature (Prov 26:27). The cross enacts this irony definitively: those who plotted Christ's death and demanded the curse 'his blood be on us and our children' (Matt 27:25) found the very condemnation they sought to impose turned back; the one who fell into the pit they dug rose out of it (Acts 2:24).</p>",
    "9": "<p>A theme: labor under fallen conditions carries inherent danger — quarrying and wood-splitting wound the worker. Christ's own labor was not exempt from this cost: he 'learned obedience through what he suffered' (Heb 5:8), and the work of redemption was accomplished through the wounds of the cross (1 Pet 2:24). The danger that attends all work 'under the sun' was borne by the one who entered the world to undo the curse that made it so.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A theme: wisdom gives the axe its edge and makes effort succeed where brute force fails. The NT redefines this: the wisdom of God is not a technique but a person (1 Cor 1:24). Christ does not overcome through worldly force — 'not by might, nor by power, but by my Spirit' (Zech 4:6, echoed in the NT's theology of weakness). The cross, the apparent opposite of 'wisdom making success,' is in fact the power by which God accomplished what the law's brute force could not (Rom 8:3-4).</p>",
    "11": "<p>A theme: if a serpent bites before it is charmed, the charmer has wasted his effort; words uncontrolled do the same damage. The tongue as a serpent is a wisdom motif developed most extensively in James 3:3-12: the tongue 'is a restless evil, full of deadly poison.' Christ's words are the contrast — controlled, healing, and life-giving (John 6:63: the words I have spoken to you are spirit and life). He tames the serpent whose bite Ecclesiastes fears.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A revelation of God: the wise person's words earn goodwill while the fool's words devour him. The divine standard of speech — words that heal and build — is embodied in Christ: 'No one ever spoke the way this man speaks' (John 7:46); 'all spoke well of him and were amazed at the gracious words that came from his lips' (Luke 4:22). His words earn goodwill even as they expose what the heart has hid (Luke 2:35).</p>",
    "13": "<p>A theme: the fool's speech begins with foolishness and ends in wicked madness — a trajectory of deterioration. The NT traces this same downward arc in the rejection of wisdom: Romans 1:21-32 describes how, beginning with the failure to honor God, the mind becomes futile and descends into disorder. Christ is Wisdom calling out from every corner (Prov 1:20-21; Matt 11:19: wisdom is proved right by her deeds), offering the alternative to this trajectory before it reaches its end.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A revelation of God: the fool multiplies words about what no human can know — the future. This verse places human knowledge of the future firmly in God's sole possession. Christ himself acknowledged this boundary with respect to his own earthly knowledge: 'But about that day or hour no one knows, not even the angels in heaven, nor the Son, but only the Father' (Matt 24:36). The Preacher and Jesus agree: presuming to know God's timetable is folly; only the Father knows.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A theme: the fool's exhausting labor cannot even accomplish the basic task of finding the city. The fruitlessness of effort disconnected from wisdom is the Preacher's recurring observation. Christ's invitation is the direct counterpoint: 'Come to me, all who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest' (Matt 11:28). The labor that exhausts without arriving is replaced by the yoke that is easy and the burden that is light (Matt 11:29-30), because it is wisdom's own yoke.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A revelation of God: woe to the land whose king is a boy — immature, self-indulgent — and whose rulers carouse in the morning. The Preacher sets out the divine standard for kingship: maturity, self-discipline, and governance for the people's good. Christ is measured against this standard and found to fulfill it perfectly: the King who fasted forty days (Matt 4:2), who refused to use his power for self-indulgence (Matt 4:3-4), and who served rather than caroused (John 13:1-17).</p>",
    "17": "<p>A shadow: blessed is the land whose king is of noble character and whose princes eat for strength, not excess. This portrait of the righteous king and ordered court anticipates the kingdom of God. Under Christ's reign — the king of noble character whose every action serves the kingdom's flourishing — the blessing the Preacher describes is realized. The eschatological feast (Rev 19:9: the marriage supper of the Lamb) is the fulfillment of eating 'for strength, not excess': abundance without indulgence in the kingdom that never ends.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A theme: laziness causes the structural collapse of the house. The image of the leaking roof and sagging rafters is applied in the NT's parable of the talents (Matt 25:14-30) and the warning against neglecting the great salvation (Heb 2:3). Christ himself is the cornerstone who holds the building together (Eph 2:20; 1 Pet 2:6); the household of God built on him does not sag, while every house built on any other foundation eventually falls (Matt 7:24-27).</p>",
    "19": "<p>A theme: feast for laughter, wine for gladness, money for everything — the Preacher's realistic assessment of creaturely life's goods. These goods are real; the NT does not negate them but transforms them. Christ's first miracle was providing wine at a feast (John 2:1-11); his last meal became the pattern for the church's worship (Luke 22:19-20); and the eschatological banquet (Rev 19:9) is the permanent form of the feasting that 'under the sun' is only temporary.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A revelation of God: do not curse the king even in your thoughts — a bird may carry your words. All speech is accountable; nothing is hidden from the one who hears. Christ intensifies this principle: 'I tell you that everyone will have to give account on the day of judgment for every empty word they have spoken' (Matt 12:36). The bird of Ecclesiastes becomes the perfect Judge of the NT: not only outward speech but the inner thoughts that produce it will be brought to light (1 Cor 4:5).</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>A shadow: cast your bread upon the waters — generous investment without visible return — and you will find it after many days. The image anticipates Christ's own pattern: his death is the bread cast into the waters of death, and the resurrection is its unexpected return. John 12:24 makes the connection explicit: 'unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains alone; but if it dies, it bears much fruit.' What the Preacher offers as wisdom, the cross enacts as history.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A theme: give a portion to seven, even to eight — generous distribution despite uncertainty about what calamity may come. This counsel of generous risk in the face of unknown disaster is fulfilled in God's own action in the gospel: 'He who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all — how will he not also, along with him, graciously give us all things?' (Rom 8:32). The liberal distribution of the gospel to all peoples, seven and eight, flows from that ultimate act of costly generosity.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A revelation of God: natural processes (rain, a falling tree) follow their own logic and cannot be redirected by human preference. The Creator's governance of creation operates with a consistency that does not bend to wishful thinking. Christ appeals to the same logic — 'he causes his sun to rise on the evil and the good, and sends rain on the righteous and the unrighteous' (Matt 5:45) — to ground the call to love enemies: the Creator does not calibrate creation's gifts by human merit, and neither should those who follow him.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A theme: paralysis through waiting for perfect conditions — watching every wind and cloud — guarantees that neither sowing nor reaping happens. The NT applies this insight to the mission of the church: 'Go therefore and make disciples of all nations' (Matt 28:19) is a command that overrides the endless waiting for the right moment. Paul's principle — 'whether in season or out of season' (2 Tim 4:2) — is the apostolic form of the Preacher's counsel: sow without waiting for favorable conditions.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A revelation of God: as you cannot know the path of the wind or the formation of bones in the womb, so you cannot know the work of God who makes everything. The hiddenness of God's creative work is one of Ecclesiastes' recurring themes. Christ's response to this mystery is not to deny it but to offer revelation: 'No one knows the Father except the Son and those to whom the Son chooses to reveal him' (Matt 11:27). The hidden work of God is made visible in Christ, who reveals the Father (John 14:9).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A theme: sow in the morning and do not rest in the evening — diligent work without knowing which effort will succeed. This describes the life of faith in the absence of guaranteed outcomes. Paul's apostolic labor operates precisely on this principle: 'I planted, Apollos watered, but God gave the growth' (1 Cor 3:6-7). The sower who goes out to sow in Christ's parable (Matt 13:3-9) does not know which ground will receive the seed; he sows everywhere, trusting the harvest to God.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A revelation of God: light is sweet and it is good for the eyes to see the sun. The Preacher affirms creaturely existence as genuinely good — to be alive and able to see is a gift. Christ claims this imagery for himself: 'I am the light of the world; whoever follows me will not walk in darkness, but will have the light of life' (John 8:12). The physical light that the Preacher calls sweet is the image of the uncreated Light that entered the world to give it permanent day.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A theme: enjoy many years, but remember that the days of darkness will be many — all that comes is vapor. The realistic frame around human joy: death awaits, and all earthly pleasure dissolves into <em>hevel</em>. Christ's resurrection breaks this frame without denying it. Death no longer has dominion over him (Rom 6:9), and for those who are in Christ, the 'days of darkness' are not the final word: 'whoever believes in him will not perish but have eternal life' (John 3:16). The vapor becomes permanent in resurrection.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A revelation of God: rejoice in your youth — but know that God will bring you into judgment. This is the key verse of the chapter: the summons to enjoy life is qualified by the absolute seriousness of divine accountability. The NT does not soften this but personalizes it: 'God has fixed a day on which he will judge the world in righteousness by a man whom he has appointed; and of this he has given assurance to all by raising him from the dead' (Acts 17:31). The resurrection is the proof that judgment is not theoretical — it has a face.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A theme: banish anxiety from your heart; childhood and youth are vapor. The call to set anxiety aside echoes in Christ's own teaching: 'Do not be anxious about your life' (Matt 6:25); 'Cast all your anxiety on him, because he cares for you' (1 Pet 5:7). The Preacher's counsel is grounded in honest realism — youth passes; the NT grounds it in a Person: anxiety about transience is answered not by denial but by the risen Christ who holds the future.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>A shadow: remember your Creator in the days of your youth, before the days of trouble come. The 'Creator' here is the unique term <em>bor'echa</em> — the one who formed you — which is the OT ground for worship: your life came from him and returns to him. In the NT this Creator became flesh: 'Through him all things were made' (John 1:3); Christ is the Creator whom Ecclesiastes calls his readers to remember. The urgency — 'before the days of trouble come' — is the NT's 'now is the acceptable time' (2 Cor 6:2).</p>",
    "2": "<p>A theme: the extended allegory of aging begins — sun, light, moon, and stars grow dark, clouds return after rain. The darkening of the heavens is the image of approaching death and its surrounding sorrows. The NT uses this same cosmic imagery for the crucifixion: 'From the sixth hour there was darkness over all the land until the ninth hour' (Matt 27:45). What the Preacher uses as an image for individual death, the gospel uses as the sign of the death that undoes death; the sun that went dark on Good Friday rises permanently on Easter.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A theme: the body's decay in the aging allegory — trembling keepers, stooped guardians, stilled grinding women, dimmed windows. The NT does not deny this physical dissolution but addresses it through the resurrection body: 'It is sown in dishonor; it is raised in glory. It is sown in weakness; it is raised in power' (1 Cor 15:43). The Son of God shared fully in this bodily deterioration (Heb 2:14-15: he shared in flesh and blood so that through death he might destroy the power of death), entering the very decay described here in order to reverse it.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A theme: the street doors shut, grinding falls silent, one rises at a bird's chirp, voices of song grow dim. The withdrawal from life's sounds and activities continues the aging allegory. Christ entered this silence too: his voice was silenced on the cross, his body buried. But the resurrection overturns this silence permanently: 'Death no longer has dominion over him' (Rom 6:9); the voice that grew dim will be heard at the last trumpet (1 Cor 15:52), calling all the silent back to life.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A theme: fear of heights, the almond tree's white blossoms (aging), the grasshopper's heaviness (appetite fails), desire fails — the person is going to their <em>bet olamo</em>, their eternal home, while the mourners walk the streets. The phrase 'eternal home' is itself significant: the grave is permanent. But Christ transforms what that 'eternal home' is for those who are his: 'In my Father's house are many rooms ... I go to prepare a place for you' (John 14:2). The mourners walking the streets outside Lazarus's tomb heard a voice that overturned their grief (John 11:43-44).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A shadow: before the silver cord is severed, the golden bowl shattered, the pitcher broken at the spring, the wheel at the well — the moment of death's irreversibility. The multiple images of breakage that cannot be undone make death's finality vivid. Christ's death was this breakage: the cord severed, the bowl shattered (the veil torn, the body broken). But the resurrection undoes the irreversibility: the shattered is restored, not to its former state but to glory (John 20:27: the wounds remain, but the person is alive). Breakage in Christ is not final.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A direct anticipation: the dust returns to the earth as it was, and the spirit returns to God who gave it. This is Ecclesiastes' clearest statement of the soul's return to its Creator, though it does not specify what that return means. The NT's answer is explicit: Christ 'committed his spirit' into the Father's hands at death (Luke 23:46: Father, into your hands I commit my spirit — citing Ps 31:5), and the resurrection vindicates that this return is not dissolution but the prelude to bodily restoration. The Preacher describes the pattern; the resurrection demonstrates its outcome.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A theme: vapor of vapors — all is vapor. The frame verse that opens the book (1:2) closes it here, placing the whole inquiry within the <em>hevel</em>-bracket. The NT does not contradict this verdict for life 'under the sun' but provides the answer to it: 'Therefore, my beloved brothers, be steadfast, immovable, always abounding in the work of the Lord, knowing that in the Lord your labor is not in vain' (1 Cor 15:58). The resurrection is the only event that makes any labor permanently non-vapor; apart from it, Ecclesiastes' verdict stands.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A revelation of God: the Teacher was wise and imparted knowledge carefully — listened, investigated, arranged proverbs with precision. This portrait of the faithful teacher who transmits wisdom for others' benefit anticipates the incarnate Teacher. Christ taught 'as one who had authority, and not as their scribes' (Matt 7:29); he arranged parables and sayings with precision (Matt 13; the Sermon on the Mount); and the Word became flesh so that what was formerly beyond reach became accessible (John 1:14).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A revelation of God: the Teacher sought pleasing words, and what he wrote was honest — words of truth. The dual standard — pleasing and true — describes the character of perfect speech, which only Christ fully embodies. Luke 4:22 records both qualities in a single verse: 'all spoke well of him and were amazed at the gracious words that came from his lips.' He is the Truth (John 14:6), and his words accomplish both effects: they are good news and they are exact; they heal and they judge.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A type: the words of the wise are like goads and like firmly driven nails — and all come from one Shepherd. The image of the singular Shepherd as the ultimate source of all wisdom is striking and points forward. The NT explicitly identifies Christ as the one Shepherd: 'I am the good shepherd ... there will be one flock, one shepherd' (John 10:11, 14, 16). All true wisdom — from the many teachers and books the verse acknowledges — is derived from the one Shepherd who laid down his life for the sheep; the collection of proverbs converges on a person.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A theme: the endless proliferation of books and the exhaustion of much study. The Preacher places all human learning in proper perspective: the accumulation of texts does not yield life. The NT offers what the many books cannot: the Word himself (John 1:14); 'these are written so that you may believe that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of God, and that by believing you may have life in his name' (John 20:31). The purpose of writing converges in the gospel; what exhausts in books finds rest in a person.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A direct anticipation: God will bring every act into judgment — every hidden thing, whether good or evil. This is the clearest eschatological declaration in Ecclesiastes, and the NT fulfills it with specificity: God has fixed the day of judgment and appointed the judge — the risen Christ (Acts 17:31). Paul's 'we must all appear before the judgment seat of Christ' (2 Cor 5:10) is the direct NT statement. The 'hidden things' — the secret acts and the inner motives Ecclesiastes could only gesture toward — will be brought to light (1 Cor 4:5: he will bring to light what is hidden in darkness and will expose the motives of the heart).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'ecclesiastes')
    merge_comm(existing, ECCLESIASTES)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'ecclesiastes', existing)
    print('Ecclesiastes 10–12 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
